column1: i was a young drag king
running on pure ego and no sleep
two jobs to support a partner who beat me
who would have parties when i should be sleeping
helped evict me when i told them she hurt me
i remember her begging me not to say anything
i remember her slamming me into a corner and wondering
why i was making excuses for her rage at me.
the friends i thought i had in the troupe started alienating me
iowa city can be so lonely
then one night at a party he groped me
the king i thought was my friend and could help me
slid his hand up my thigh and said nothing
girlfriend by his side i convinced myself it was an accident but there was no apology
just the loudest silence i've ever heard next to my insides screaming
why didnt he just ask me?
where could i ever find safety?
he only wanted the same things she did to me
to use me how they wanted
when i got home that night she abused me
for going out on the town while she was home sick
like this happened because i was out alone like she warned me
i was scared if i told her she'd blame me
and hurt me again for my supposed deceit
all of a sudden this town seemed conspired to kill everything inside of me.
how could this happen to me?
these were women wrapped up in misogyny.
i still cant tell that troupe this story.
drafted an email 100 times what's the point?
i'm still convinced they dont care about me.
i'm still scared they wont believe me.
#poetry #poetsofinstagram #metoo #ickings #thecultivatedfool (i'm still too scared to actually say anything. they are still performing. i'll probably delete this bc i'm still scared.)";;en;#poetry

column1: 320073;instagram;2018-10-02 16:43:11;FALSE;"#whyididntreport few know about the interactions i had while dating through apps like tinder and okcupid. majority of the people i met were decent people
column2: and then you get the one who makes you delete the app and never use it again.

column1: it was a week or so since i had gone out with friends
column2: i had been sick all week and had major cabin fever. i was also talking to this guy from tinder who worked at a local bar. he also lived in my neighborhood with roommates.

column1: i decided to get out and surprise him by visiting the bar with a friend for drinks. he recognized me from my pictures and made me a special cocktail. it was delicious. he sat and talked with us at our table for a bit and we decided he was cool enough to hang out with us that night. we went to another friends house for drinking games and to hang out.

it was getting late and i was going to head home. i offered to give him a ride back as well since we lived only a couple miles apart. when i drove up to his place he invited me inside. i followed him in
column2: it turned out none of his roomies were in town that weekend. i quickly got the fear of being alone in a stranger's house.

column1: that fear saved me from what could have been really terrible. as i was about to leave
column2: he was begging me to stay and started pushing me against the wall and even slapped me asking me to tell him i loved him. i ran out the front door and got in my car
column3: crying i called my friend who was still at my other friends house. she told me to call the cops. i never did
column4: in fear he was so close to my home and knew where i worked. i just let the memory fade
column5: he was probably so drunk he forgot about it the next day.

column1: i would hope other women using those apps will be more safe than i was and even if your friends seem ok with that person
column2: you still have no idea who he really is.

column1: 320168;instagram;2018-10-02 15:40:40;FALSE;"@regran_ed from @dr_with_a_good_handwriting - in response to the question asked by @shespeaksforthechange: "" separate queues for women- right or wrong?"" let's take a simple example. two people a and b are supposed to do the given work in the given time. they both are equally capable. but person a is given more attention
column3: and more responsibility. though a and b do the same work and they both are equally efficient
column4: a is given recognition and better rewards.  b is mistreated
column5: a is valued more and there is a general misconception that a is better. so whenever there is a job to be done
column6: people want a to do it. now somebody (say x) comes along and sees that this is not fair. x tries to give equal opportunities to a and b by suggesting that a certain percentage of the work will always be done by b
column7: so that people appreciate b's work and also understand that they both are equally capable.

column1: reservation for women or separate queues for public services is not against feminism. there's a difference between equality and equity. equality is sameness
in every part of the world
column2: in every culture women have been oppressed. patriarchy decided that women couldn't vote
column5: or even dress as they want to. we all know that even today we're still fighting for our rights. rights over our bodies
column7: our actions. coming to the question
column8: if separate queues for women is fair. my answer is 'yes'
column9: but with a hope that i'll be able to answer 'no' after a few years. we have separate coaches in trains
column10: because women suffered harassment in general coaches. we have 33% reservation in government services
column11: because girls are not given the opportunity to get good quality education
column12: and men are preferred by employers because they think women are too emotional to handle work. we're still struggling you see. that's why we need these props to hasten the process of development. but hopefully
column13: after a few years when men and women are considered absolutely equal in every part of the world
column14: by every community; that would be the time we won't require separate queues or separate coaches or reservations.<---continued in the first comment--->";;en;;@Regran_ed

column1: 10 years ago when i was 16 a much older friend of mine tried to rape me. i won't go into gory details but it was scary and traumatic and to this day i still don't fully understand it all. i never told any mutual friends it happened
column2: i doubt it would've mattered. i told only the partner i was with at the time. i blocked my attacker on all social media (only fb back then) and stopped participating in social circles he was involved in (effectively all my social circles too). since then he's only come up in conversation when i have brought him up. he's always just been a monster in my story
column3: a fairytale villain. unexpectedly today his name was brought up at work. he's known by the gamers i hang out with at work
column4: and whilst he apparently only shows up once in a blue moon
column5: thats still closer to him that i ever want to be. his name cropping up outside of my control has reminded me with a huge bump that he is real
column8: his body all belong to a real person. my body has been flushed with panic since he was mentioned
column9: it was a long time ago and he can not hurt me now but that doesn't stop me feeling sick. expressing my feelings here often helps so i'm hoping writing down my feelings will calm me. i will be ok

column1: its not about men vs women...and if we keep thinking or addressing feminism in this way we might as well not bring actual injustices to light. ive recently been around men who are genuinly bitter and annoyed with movements such as #metoo...they are angered by feminists and spit ugly at woman who stand up and respect themselves. i find this incredibly sad. i am single and i get asked way too often why this is...i divert back to asking why are so many males intermidated by strong females? ive been asked way too many times to simmer down
column2: been told i talk to much when i speak truth...hahahaha maybe ill be single forever and the real reason would be the imbalance in real men. right now women are evolving...i hope im still around to see a revolution where men celebrate justice
column4: humility and the feminine energy within themselves...because real men cry
column5: real men feel emotion and are intune with it

column2: the vishuddha (throat) chakra & a synchronous meeting -

column1: brahmari breath (bee breath) is one of my favorite breath practices. i love practicing this in class with a room full of people all humming like bees. it involves inhaling through the noise and humming the breath out on the exhale
column2: so the exhale is extended. this down regulates the autonomic nervous system into the parasympathetic (rest and digest.) it is a very grounding practice that can help with insomnia
column4: stress and depression. it can help to strengthen the voice and balance the vishuddha (throat) chakra
column6: communication & the power of choice.  i have a story to tell about all of this. growing up and as an adult
column7: i've found it very difficult to express my needs or speak my truth with a powerful voice. this is changing. what is going on in america at the moment with christine ford speaking her truth alongside many others in the #metoo movement gives me strength. trump still being elected as president after openly admitting to sexually assaulting women
column8: is an integral part of the back drop to my story
column9: to a culture that made me learn to silence myself. that is all part of this story but not a part i want to go into today
column10: though it is very important to mention briefly for context.  so long story short
column11: i found myself in india on my yoga teacher training course nearly 2 yeas ago
column12: which was for me a place & time of deep healing. i met wonderful krishna @urbanyogikrishna who recognised blockage in my vishuddha chakra and helped me to begin the journey of finding my voice and feeling confident in expressing my truth.  in appreciation & celebration of learning brahmari breath in india and of setting the intention to strengthen my voice & clear my blocked throat chakra after speaking with krishna
column13: i have drawn a picture of her. when the eyes and ears are gently closed as shown
column14: this draws the focus inwards by symbolically shutting the mind off from the senses in a state of pratyahara (sense withdrawal) in preparation for meditation.

column2: i enjoy feeling into the stillness that is left.

column1: 320611;instagram;2018-10-02 10:09:58;FALSE;"sebut saja aku bunga. umurku 28 tahun sekarang. dlm keluarga besar
column2: aku adalah anak paling bungsu. kami tinggal didesa dimana norma adat dan agama sangat dijunjung tinggi. saat aku berumur 6 tahun
column4: sebut saja namanya tob mengajakku bermain permainan baru yang tak pernah ku pahami. saat itu dia kelas 2 sma dan sedang libur sekolah (dia tidak tinggal bersama kami
column5: karena dia sekolah di kota). selama libur
column6: saat tidak ada orang dirumah dia mengajariku permainan itu. aku berusaha menolak
column7: tetapi dia membujuk (memaksa) ku. aku pun turut padanya.

column1: begitu permainan itu terus kami lakukan
column2: setiap dia libur sekolah.  dia mengatakan permainan itu rahasia dan tidak boleh ku ceritakan pada siapapun. jika aku memberitahu pada orang lain maka aku akan dibuang ke sungai.

column1: aku tidak pernah menikmati permainan itu. aku berusaha menghindar setiap dia libur. aku pergi kerumah tetangga
column3: bahkan aku ngotot ikut ke ladang bersama ibu.

column2: aku harus ikut ke ladang jika tob tidak ikut
column3: aku tidak mau dirumah bersama dia"" kataku suatu saat pada ibu. tetapi sedikit pun ibu tidak curiga.

column2: tob menikah. mereka tinggal di kota. aku lega. aku tidak perlu takut lagi. selama 2 tahun aku takut dan tersiksa dengan ""permainan"" itu. 4 tahun kemudian dia berpisah dengan istrinya
column3: dia pulang ke rumah bersama seorang anaknya (ponakan ku). inilah sumber petaka itu.
ada pesta saudara di desa lain. semua pergi kesana kecuali aku

column2: seperti biasa. untuk pertama kalinya aku berdoa agar selamat dari ""permainan"" itu. belum sempat aku tertidur
column3: aku mendengar seseorang datang ke tempat tidur ku. aku jantungan. aku menangis memanggil tuhan dalam diam agar menyelamatkan ku. tob mendekat
column4: aku semakin menangis. aku memberontak saat dia membuka bajuku. aku lari
column5: tapi gadis kecil ini ditangkap lagi dan diikat. tanganku diikat dan mulutku disumpal. aku tau ini bukan lagi permainan. aku terus menutup mataku
column6: aku tidak mau melihatnya. dia terus membuka paksa pakaianku. lalu

column1: it happened to me when i was 14 years old on my way to my 9th grade gratuation party at the art shcool i was attending .
a man who was a complete stranger to me
column3: rubbed himself on be and forcefully touched my privets.

column2: shook him out of me and ran away as fast as i could arriving to the party as a complete mess.

column1: it took me some long minutes to get myself together and proceed with my role in the graduation celebrations... and then it took me years before i told anyone about what had happen to me that day.
i haven't told neither because i felt ashamed nor because i was in denial. i didn't feel as a victim and wasn't embarrassed about what had happen to me.
i made a choise to put this nasty incident behind me and move on forward brave and strong!!!! obviously it left a stamp on me
column2: a scar one of many i got living through life
column3: but being a strong woman it is in my character not to let other people decide for me or navigate the course of my life!

column1: 320663;instagram;2018-10-02 09:30:48;FALSE;"i think golden hour is one of my favorite times of day.

over the past few weeks i have been going through my sexual assault in explicit detail with my counselor and it has really pulled my emotions completely out into disarray. i feel like i never know where i stand with anyone and am second guessing everything. yet
column2: i feel so grateful to have friends that consistently lift me up and remind me of my value when my irrationality gets the better of me. i've been an exhausted emotional state in a constantly overwhelmed mode. they're the keepers you know: @gerald_nordqvist @xkimnn @ottilieclarke @theonlytreva @unpheonix @chloeekempp @joshquickk i can honestly say i've never felt more supported even when i feel alone and never felt more authentically loved even when i can't hold myself up. some of them probably don't even realise how badly i needed that conversation or laugh or snapchat but these are my people. i'm all about quality over quantity and i think i've hit the jackpot. thank you to all of you especially
column3: each of you are the silver linings in my irrationality that helps ground me.";;en;;@gerald_nordqvist

column1: the first time madeleine was raped
column2: she was 13 years old. when she woke the following morning
column7: urinated on and tied up over a period of almost five hours. both men had violently abused her - but her friend appeared to have been untouched. they agreed never to speak of the night again so madeleine lived in silence for years. the rape impacted her persona immediately: first by retreating into herself and then by engaging in self-destructive behaviours. throughout her teens
column8: madeleine was raped a further three times by three separate attackers. each time
column9: she blamed herself. it was only when she met her now husband that she realised she couldn't let these men ruin her life any more. he showed her love and patience and
column10: despite her initial concerns about the invasive nature of childbirth
column11: they went on to have three healthy
column12: happy daughters. madeleine went through various forms of therapy over many years which eventually led her to publicly share her story with the forgiveness project. once she'd spoken out
column13: she realised she could raise awareness of violence against women and girls and help others find their voice

column1: 320687;instagram;2018-10-02 07:54:48;FALSE;"i was gonna post something quite different today. but things being as they are i canâ€™t keep quiet. (remember that @milckmusic song?)

the truth is i am just so tired. and sad. and angry. i am tired of finding out about all the ways in which we are losing what we thought was a given or a hard won certitude. i am tired of the lack of common sense and empathy that plagues our world. it makes me sick.
to quote an amazing opinion piece by alexandra petri:
â€œsomeday i want to not be tired.
someday i want us not to apologize.
women are used to squinting to see our own stories in the stories of others. to reading ourselves into the words â€œall men are created equal.â€â€

for me this quote is everything. we shouldnâ€™t have to fit ourselves between the lines. we shouldnâ€™t have to see history repeat itself. we shouldnâ€™t have to keep fighting for the same damn things over and over again for decadesâ€¦

column2: i was in the middle of an abusive relationship that nobody knew was happening. on one of the rough nights
column3: i left the house in a hurry and sped 30+ minutes to my favorite open mic
column4: even though i knew it would be ending shortly after i got there.  i walked in late
column6: but the hot pink fuzzy slippers that i had on with my work shirt and skirt wouldnâ€™t let me.  a couple of my poet friends joked my choice of footwear
column7: not knowing that iâ€™d ran out of the house in my stockinged feet and the slippers were all i had in my car.  i remember smiling at a few people before slipping to the back of the room and pretending to be invisible.  i wanted to be invisible.  it would be years before my friend
column9: would tell me that she would never forget the look on my face when iâ€™d walked in that room.  it would be years before i would tell her what i had gone through.  tonight
column10: a few friends and i celebrated her birthday and the beginning of domestic violence awareness month with dinner at a local restaurant holding a fundraiser for g.r.o.w. foundation and we had a great time! but for me
column11: it was also a reminder of the importance of having friends who will fight for you and with you.  i have an amazing support system of family and friends and i bet that many of you do too! talk to them.  lean on them.  you are not alone.  even and especially during the moments when you think you are. - âœ¨nchâœ¨

column1: 320979;instagram;2018-10-02 02:29:17;FALSE;"three years ago we set this up! it looks rather different now; more yarn
column4: and of course the addition of extra furniture in the room. i was so happy after all the squares had been stuffed full
column5: and i could stand back to see this wave of colour in my own safe space. somewhere to retreat and enjoy and think and craft and read... when you have factors to your life that are dominating
column7: sometimes it is hard to escape from them
column8: and letting them become all consuming. my craft room is my escape. it lets me get away from being disabled
column9: it helps me put my pain to one side if only for a moment when i choose a yarn
column10: it allows me to be something more. more than my illnesses
column11: more than merely a wheelchair.  i am a woman with a voice. and this space to breathe allows that voice to speak. .
